By 7 December, [[UNICEF]] had secured sufficient international donor funding to provide sufficient water treatment chemicals for three weeks water supply for Harare and had arranged a shipment of chemical sufficient for four months supply.<ref name=oxfam2/> UNICEF distributed 360,000 litres of water per day in Harare, as well as handing out soap and buckets.<ref name=overwhelmed/> Notwithstanding the contributions received, UNICEF indicated on 9 December 2008 that US$17,500,000 was needed to respond properly to the outbreak.<ref name=descent>{{cite news|url=http://www.reliefweb.int/rw/rwb.nsf/db900sid/MCOI-7M8MGB?OpenDocument&rc=1&emid=ACOS-635PHU|title=Zimbabwe: Tracking the Descent|date=11 Dec 2008|publisher=ReliefWeb|accessdate=2008-12-12}}</ref> As of 15 December, following agreement with the Zimbabwe government, the [[World Health Organization]] was procuring medical supplies to roll out a response plan to run health centres.<ref name=tollup>{{cite news|url=http://www.reliefweb.int/rw/rwb.nsf/db900SID/MYAI-7MD5EL?OpenDocument&rc=1&emid=ACOS-635PHU|title=Zimbabwe cholera death toll nears 1,000, UN reports|date=15 Dec 2008|publisher=United Nations News Service|accessdate=2008-12-16}}</ref>

==Spread beyond Zimbabwe==
[[File:Spread of Zimbabwean Cholera Outbreak.svg|350px|thumb|right|Spread of cholera within southern Africa, as of 10 February 2009. Not all cases are part of the 2008–2009 Zimbabwean cholera outbreak. <br>'''Key:'''<br><span style="color:red;">█</span> Deaths recorded<br>
<span style="color:orange;">█</span> Infections recorded]]
The cholera outbreak spread during 2008 to districts in [[Botswana]], [[Mozambique]], [[South Africa]] and [[Zambia]] bordering Zimbabwe.<ref name= Milliband/><ref name=collapse/>

===South Africa===
The outbreak spread to the Zimbabwean migrant worker community in [[Limpopo]] and [[Mpumalanga]] provinces of South Africa<ref name=crosses>{{cite news|url=http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/IRIN/4d2d97e46fa9854480cd3d665a8a49bf.htm|title=SOUTH AFRICA-ZIMBABWE: Cholera crosses the border too|date=19 Nov 2008|publisher= IRIN via Reuters|accessdate=2008-11-19}}</ref> and cholera bacteria were detected in the [[Limpopo River]] on 3 December 2008.<ref name=descent/> By 12 December 2008 11 deaths and 859 infections had been recorded in South Africa.<ref name=bulletin12dec>{{cite news|url=http://www.reliefweb.int/rw/rwb.nsf/db900SID/EGUA-7MCQLR?OpenDocument&rc=1&emid=ACOS-635PHU|title=Zimbabwe health cluster weekly bulletin No. 2 - 12 Dec 2008|date=12 Dec 2008|publisher=World Health Organisation|accessdate=2008-12-16}}</ref> This rose to 2,100 cases and 15 deaths by 14 January 2009<ref name=neighboursrise>{{cite news|url=http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5inUrjOec8guxoAGDFfCrqaftxyMQ|title=Zimbabwe cholera surges as neighbours report rising cases|date=15 Jan 2009|publisher=AFP|accessdate=2009-01-15}}</ref> and to 12,000 cases and 59 deaths by 10 March.<ref>[http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5gLRGT2fcbFvRKCiIagnxkaRGodHA AFP S.Africa cholera outbreak 'declining']</ref>

The [[South African government]] set up medical facilities and drinking water supplies at the [[Beitbridge]] border post<ref name=border>{{cite news|url=http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?set_id=1&click_id=68&art_id=vn20081204051853844C776011|title=SA–Zim border under close watch |date=4 Dec 2008|publisher=Independent Online (South Africa)| accessdate=2008-12-04}}</ref> and deployed the National Outbreak Response Team and additional medical personnel to [[Musina]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Statement by Minister of Health Barbara Hogan on the outbreak of cholera in Zimbabwe and South Africa|url=http://www.info.gov.za/speeches/2008/08112711451003.htm|date=26 Nov 2008|publisher=SA Government Information Service|accessdate=2009-01-22}}</ref> [[Anthony Turton]], a [[political scientist]] and Unit Fellow with the [[Council for Scientific and Industrial Research]] (CSIR) in South Africa, who had earlier warned of the risk of cholera in South Africa and wrote a report that recommended that the South African government increase its spending on water treatments lest a cholera outbreak occur in the country,<ref name="environment.co.za"/> was suspended for having made "inappropriate statements to the media".<ref name=turton>{{cite news| url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/7752682.stm|title=South Africa at risk of cholera|date=27 Nov 2008|publisher=BBC|accessdate= 2008-12-09}}</ref> On 10 December 2008, the Limpopo Provincial Government declared [[Vhembe District Municipality]], which borders Zimbabwe at Beitbridge, [[Matabeleland South]] province, a disaster area.<ref name=nocholera/> On a 28 January 2009 visit to [[Musina]] with high-ranking [[Government of South Africa|government]] and [[African National Congress|ruling party]] officials, [[South African Health Ministry|Health Minister]] [[Barbara Hogan]] said
{{quote|Cholera is spreading... We are beginning to see a shift from Zimbabwe to South Africa. The situation is scary... I am concerned about the impact this is having on our provinces.<ref name=scary>{{cite news|title=Cholera situation is ‘scary’, says Hogan|date=28 Jan 2009|publisher=The Times (South Africa)|url=http://www.thetimes.co.za/News/Article.aspx?id=926867|accessdate=2009-01-29}}</ref> }}

===Other countries===
The spread of the outbreak to Zimbabwe's other neighbouring countries was initially slower than in South Africa, with one death recorded in [[Districts of Zambia#Lusaka Province|Kafue District]] in Zambia and none in Botswana or [[Namibia]] by 9 December 2008.<ref name= redalert/> However as 2009 came, cases have increased, with 4,354 cases and 55 deaths reported by 10 February 2009 in Zambia and 1,596 cases and 14 deaths in [[Katanga Province|Katanga]], the southernmost province of the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo|DR Congo]].<ref name=rel>{{cite web|url=http://www.reliefweb.int/rw/rwb.nsf/db900SID/EGUA-7PKQ35?OpenDocument|title=Africa weekly emergency situation update Vol. 2, No. 8|author=[[World Health Organization]]|publisher=ReliefWeb|accessdate=2009-02-28}}</ref> In Mozambique, cholera has spread to 10 out of 11 provinces,<ref name=rel/> with a total of 9,533 cases by 1 Jan to 1 Mar 2009  and 119 deaths by 17 March <ref name="afp119">[http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5iUhFqAALo1-pIJv3OKCajIZW0Jsw AFP:12 Mozambican prisoners die after cholera riot]</ref> – as well as the deaths of four health workers in a mob attack, blamed on "misinformation and misunderstanding in efforts to combat cholera".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.apanews.net/apa.php?page=show_article_eng&id_article=90608|publisher=APAnews|title=Mob kills health workers in Mozambique over cholera deaths|date=3 Mar 2009|accessdate=2009-03-03}}</ref> with 12 of the prisoners from the incident having died in jail.<ref name="afp119"/> In Malawi 104 deaths were recorded since January, making it the worst outbreak since 2001-2002 where 960 people died.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://af.reuters.com/article/topNews/idAFJOE52J0KJ20090320|publisher=Reuters|title=Malawi: Malawi says cholera outbreak kills 104|date=20 Mar 2009|accessdate=2009-03-22}}</ref>  Southern Africa is not the only outbreak of cholera in Africa, Kenya, Somalia, Tanzania, DRC, and Ghana have had unrelated cholera outbreaks with between 10-100 deaths in 2009 as of February.<ref name=rel/>

